<taxonomicName authority="(Forsskal in Niebuhr 1775)" authorityName="Forsskal in Niebuhr" authorityYear="1775" baseAuthorityName="Forsskal in Niebuhr" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[151,719,1273,1298]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Holocentridae" genus="Neoniphon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Beryciformes" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sammara">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,394,1273,1298]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Neoniphon sammara</emphasis>
(Forsskål in Niebuhr 1775)
</taxonomicName>
—Bloodspot squirrelfish (
<figureCitation box="[1030,1113,1273,1298]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="82.[151,250,1397,1419]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,411,1375]" captionTargetId="figure@82.[151,1437,411,1375]" captionTargetPageId="82" captionText="FIGURE 27. Myripristis violacea Bleeker 1851 (lower) and Neoniphon sammara (Forsskål in Niebuhr 1775) (upper), Lissenung Island, Kavieng District, 5 m depth, 6 July 2011 (underwater photograph: Dean Tully)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2988391/files/figure.png" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
)
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="83.[151,1436,1273,1622]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,416,1309,1334]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
Status at 
<collectingRegion box="[261,411,1309,1334]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="New Ireland" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">New Ireland</collectingRegion>
.
</emphasis>
First recorded from St. Mathias as 
<taxonomicName authority="Valenciennes, 1829" authorityName="Valenciennes" authorityYear="1829" baseAuthorityName="Forsskål" baseAuthorityYear="1775" box="[811,1069,1309,1334]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Holocentridae" genus="Holocentrum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Beryciformes" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sammara">
<emphasis box="[811,1069,1309,1334]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Holocentrum sammara</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Duncker, G. &amp; Mohr, E." box="[1111,1381,1309,1334]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="57 - 84" refId="ref186462" refString="Duncker, G. &amp; Mohr, E. (1929) Die Fische der Sudsee-Expedition der Hamburgischen Wissenschaftlichen Stiftung 1908 - 1909. 3. Teil. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Staatsinstitut und Zoologischen Museum in Hamburg, 44, 57 - 84." type="journal article" year="1929">Duncker &amp; Mohr (1929</bibRefCitation>
: 71), based on 
<accessionNumber box="[261,405,1345,1369]" httpUri="http://www.uniprot.org/uniprot/ZMH11999" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">ZMH 11999</accessionNumber>
, record confimed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Kotlyar, A. N." box="[653,817,1345,1370]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" pagination="170 - 189" refId="ref190497" refString="Kotlyar, A. N. (1998) Species composition and distribution of holocentrids in the oceans of the world (Holocentridae, Beryciformes). Foprosy Ikhtiologii, 38 (2), 199 - 217. [In Russian. English translation in Journal of Ichthyology, 38 (2), 170 - 189.]" type="journal article" year="1998">Kotlyar (1998</bibRefCitation>
: 205). A specimen photographed at Lissenung Island, Kavieng District, 
<quantity box="[355,401,1381,1406]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" unit="m" value="5.0">5 m</quantity>
depth, by Dean Tully on 
<date box="[700,837,1381,1406]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" value="2011-07-06">6 July 2011</date>
; a video of a specimen taken in Alexander Passage, southeast of New Hanover, at 
<quantity box="[489,574,1417,1442]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" metricValueMax="14.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" unit="m" value="9.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="5.0">5–14 m</quantity>
depth, St. KR96, in 2014 (identified by Barry C. Russell).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="83" pageNumber="84" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="83.[151,1436,1273,1622]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,497,1453,1478]" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion box="[504,649,1453,1478]" country="Papua New Guinea" name="New Ireland" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">New Ireland</collectingRegion>
: 1, 2, 4.—General distribution: Red Sea, East Africa, 
<collectingCountry box="[1253,1388,1453,1478]" name="Madagascar" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
and Mascarenes east to Line Islands and 
<collectingCountry box="[578,665,1489,1514]" name="Pitcairn" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Pitcairn</collectingCountry>
Group, north to southern 
<collectingCountry box="[969,1036,1490,1513]" name="Japan" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Japan</collectingCountry>
, Ogasawara and Hawaiian islands, south to Western Australia at 
<geoCoordinate box="[479,569,1526,1550]" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" precision="925" value="-20.55">20°33'S</geoCoordinate>
, Lord Howe Island, 
<collectingCountry box="[796,866,1526,1550]" name="Tonga" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Tonga</collectingCountry>
and Rapa. Found in seagrass beds and hard bottom habitats on lagoon and seaward coral and rocky reefs, often associated with branching 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Oken, 1815-" authorityYear="1815" box="[1159,1266,1562,1585]" class="Anthozoa" family="Acroporidae" genus="Acropora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scleractinia" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1159,1266,1562,1585]" italics="true" pageId="83" pageNumber="84">Acropora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
coral, 
<quantity box="[1348,1436,1561,1586]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="4.6" metricValueMin="0.0" pageId="83" pageNumber="84" unit="m" value="23.0" valueMax="46.0" valueMin="0.0">0–46 m</quantity>
depth. Marine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
